<br>
Obviously, Race is a factor in life, so totally ignoring it would be naive.  But I applaud the rejection of the points-type system because I think those tend to overweight Race.  Even if it is only worth a small amount, when two candidates are otherwise equal that extra few points becomes a tie-breaker, effectively favoring one over the other.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, open ended systems are going to be more open to future suits, simply because they can not transparently explain how the decisions are made in a simple manner.  But the alternative, which is to use a math formula a la points, is an inferior method in all ways.<br>
<br>
My general take on Affirmative Action in general is that often they completely miss the point.  Affirmative Action is supposed to provide EQUAL OPPORTUNITY.  To be honest, University, Graduate Schools, and Employment are too LATE in the process to provide that.  Equal Opportunity programs really should target much younger children.<br>
<br>
And because Equal OPPORTUINTY can not be easily measured and reported on, what they seem to settle on is a policy of enforcing EQUAL RESULTS, which is a wholly different animal. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=syllestraefv>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3060<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/24/03 1:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=521.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Michigan Affirmative Action.</span><hr size=1> Affirmative action is a Trojan Horse.<br>
<br>
It pretends it's there to help minority students.  In reality, it helps corporations.<br>
<br>
Corporations like / need to have a balanced workforce (from a racial perspective), so affirmative action gives them a more balanced pool of collegiates to look at.<br>
<br>
The college students who would be helped by affirmative action don't really need the help more than anyone else.  <br>
<br>
The hispanic &amp; asian primary school students who are learning English as a second language, they could use some help.<br>
<br>
The black primary school students who are in low income areas with crappy and/or dangerous schools, they could use some help.<br>
<br>
The way to put minorities on equal footing with non-minorities is to address the problem where it begins, not tackle the symptoms of it 10 years down the road.  <br>
<br>
In this &quot;No kid left behind&quot; crap, the schools that are doing well get more funding, and the schools doing poorly receive less.  We have all this standardized testing stuff here in Washington, schools that perform well get more funding, schools that perform poorly get less.  <br>
<br>
I'm sure in someone's head, that's a good way to motivate schools to work harder at teaching their kids or something.  In reality it just diverts even more funding away from the schools that need it.  <br>
<br>
You don't need to take race into account <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>at all</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to help fix this problem, you just need to use some common sense and some compassion.  Unfortunately both of those are in short supply in politics.<br>
<br>
- Syll <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=syllestraefv>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3061<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/24/03 1:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=521.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Michigan Affirmative Action.</span><hr size=1> As an aside, and sorry if this sounds racist, speaking specifically about blacks in this country... black people, as a group, are never going to see success in this country until they start taking responsibility for getting it themselves.<br>
<br>
Sure, you'll hear black politicians trashing standardized testing, saying that asking a student how to divide 12 cupcakes among 4 children is racist because black kids can't afford cupcakes or some crap, but you don't hear them trashing the rap industry for presenting the image that you don't need an education to succeed, all you need is your badass crib &amp; a gun or whatever.<br>
<br>
I'm half black.  My dad &amp; his siblings are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>one</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> generation removed from poor black farmers in Alabama.  When he was young an apple was honestly a treat for him because they couldn't afford much fresh fruit.  So what happened to by dad &amp; his siblings?  Did they live a life of oppression in this white man's world?<br>
<br>
Um... no.  They worked their asses off in school and made something of themselves.  My dad is a VP at his company.  One of his brothers was a college football coach &amp; now athletic director.  One of his brothers is an engineer.  One of his brothers is a police sargeant (sp).  One of his brothers owns an auto-repair shop.  One of his brothers works at the phone company.  His sister became a stay at home mom to better raise her kids.<br>
<br>
None of them got into drugs.  None of them ran with gangs.  Money didn't fall from the sky, they worked their way into success.  My dad joined RoTC to help pay for his schooling (and later fought in vietnam).  I think some of his siblings did the same, others earned scholarships, others just worked their way through school.<br>
<br>
The point is, my grandma had 7 kids, all of them black.  She and my grandpa were poor and uneducated.  My grandfather was a self-taught auto-mechanic, and did such good work that he  attracted a wealthy clientele that wanted dings repaired in their fancy foreign cars etc, and that help put food on the table.  Sadly, he was murdered by one of his friends.  That didn't stop my grandma from raising their kids well, and it didn't stop the kids from being successful.  There is no affirmative action program in the world that can provide people with an attitude towards becoming successful.  That needs to come from within the culture, and right now black culture is doing a lousy job of getting that message out to it's children.<br>
<br>
And blacks can blame whites until the end of time for where they are right now, but it's not going to change anything.  <br>
<br>
