<br>
I don't know where to find it, but I remember about a year ago, one of the news programs here conducted a study on current hiring practices and discrimination. They submitted job applications with exactly equal qualifications to companies. The only difference was the names they had put on the applications. On one application, they put a common &quot;white sounding&quot; name, i.e. Barbara Miller, and on the other they put a &quot;black sounding&quot; name like Lacrishia Jackson or something to that effect. (I'm sure you get the idea). Anyway, the applications with the black sounding names were rejected and they didn't attempt to call the person for an interview. With the white sounding names, they attempted to call that person in for the interview. Was this a shock to any minorities? Heck no. It confirmed what we knew all along.<br>
With my personal experiences, back in the late 80's, I would call around looking for jobs. Although Spanish is my first language, I don't have a hint of an accent now. Over the phone, I &quot;sound&quot; white. I told them my qualifications over the phone and they would sound very excited to interview me. I would get dressed up really nice and professional and walk in feeling confident. The interviewer would take one look at me, and I KNEW right then and there they weren't going to hire me. This was at a place that told me over the phone that they could not find anyone that could speak English well. Although I haven't looked for a job recently, Im sure the same thing goes on today. <br>
Basically, my point is, racial discrimination is not dead, it's alive and well. Syll has the right idea though with minorities empowering themselves through economic successes. It's just harder in this society to achieve for the minority, but it can be done <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.insight.rr.com/kindredwolf/Shaila2.gif " style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vampiricmuse>Vampiric Muse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Blood is sexah ;)</span><br>  Posts: 268<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/24/03 8:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=521.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://eqsighost.netfirms.com/DavidStrange/vamp.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Michigan Affirmative Action.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Basically, my point is, racial discrimination is not dead, it's alive and well.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
