<br>
The definition of affirmative action is this...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Main Entry: affirmative action<br>
Function: noun<br>
Date: 1965<br>
: an active effort to improve the employment or educational opportunities of members of minority groups and women<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I just happen to think that you can meet that goal, as defined, w/o taking race or gender into consideration.<br>
<br>
When you directly take those things into account, you automatically generate the same kind of unfairness that you're trying to alleviate.  Not only that, but you foster feelings of animosity on the part of men &amp; whites against those other groups, rather than bringing them together.<br>
<br>
Let's take hispanics as an example.  There is a noticable gap between the educational performance of hispanics -vs- that of white students.  A very large portion of this gap is due to language barrier... English is a second language for a lot of these students.  You can address the issue by putting funding out there for good ESL programs to help bring the students on par with those who are native speakers.  The manner in which you have addressed the problem is now blind to race (it's focused on non-native english speakers), and white students aren't put in the position of feeling that any unfairness has been perpetrated on them.<br>
<br>
When it comes to college entrance, most colleges do <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>not</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> discriminate on the basis of gender or race, except in <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>favor</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of minorities.  Why?  Because diversity on campus is considered a preferable trait for a college.  They <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>want</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> minority students.  Affirmative action at this level is more or less in place to address the issue of there not being proportionately as many minority applicants of equal skill as white students.  But addressing it at the college level is thus the wrong place to be dealing with it, because you will <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>always</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> have that problem.  You need to address it where it starts (in primary school), and in a manner that's blind to race in the first place (even if the effects of your program end up benefitting a minority group more).<br>
<br>
- Syll <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vampiricmuse>Vampiric Muse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Blood is sexah ;)</span><br>  Posts: 272<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/25/03 6:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=521.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://eqsighost.netfirms.com/DavidStrange/vamp.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Michigan Affirmative Action.</span><hr size=1> Like you said Syll, in colleges it happens in reverse.  That happens in the workplace at certain areas also.  Some people don't like black people and therefore will bias against them.  Some people don't like white, same thing.  HOWEVER,<br>
