<br>
You call a lot of &quot;bullshit&quot; on statements about racial discrimination, but you don't put forth a single shred of evidence that disproves that racism in hiring practices exists, other than &quot;well, it could just be that it was you, and not your race.&quot;<br>
<br>
The &quot;experiment&quot; that involves sending out resumes with &quot;white&quot; names (Jennifer Smythe)...&quot;black names&quot; (Latisha Williams)...and &quot;hispanic&quot; names (Maria Gutierrez) all with the same resume is done regularly, usually a couple times a year by tv news shows, newspaper reporters, etc...  Every time it's been done, there is a significantly higher response rate to &quot;white&quot; names over &quot;minority&quot; names.<br>
<br>
As for your comment about Asians doing well, the problem there is almost a reverse racism.  Asians are considered the &quot;model minority&quot;, and have the stereotype of &quot;all extremely intelligent, all have a work ethic that values job over family over self, all highly educated.&quot;  It's not a whites vs. everyone else thing, it's really a &quot;cultural view&quot; of what race is.  Asians are not considered lazy and uneducated by &quot;American culture.&quot;  However, the stereotype hits a lot harder on other minorities.<br>
<br>
I worked in the human resources department of a large company.  The people in charge of hiring there were largely fair and good people, giving everyone an equal chance.  But when you're going through a pile of resumes, it was difficult to resist the impulse to associate &quot;Juanita Lopez&quot; with the last Hispanic woman you interviewed, the one who could hardly speak a word of English and couldn't comprehend what the job even entailed.  You shouldn't do that.  And they'd try hard to resist it.  But it happened.  People got shafted because of their names and appearances, despite the best human efforts not to have it happen.  And these were good people.<br>
<br>
There are bad people too.<br>
<br>
My father and 2 colleagues were once responsible for filling three vacancies in their department by interviewing the 4 top candidates.  Two white males, one white female, and one black male.  After the interviews, one of my father's colleagues, leaned back in his chair and said, &quot;I guess we know who's not getting this job.  We have enough damn *slur deleted* out working on the factory floor to not be hiring them into management.&quot;  This wasn't some old redneck in the deep south saying this shit.  This was a 30 year old family man in suburban Chicago.  It's not *usually* so blatant, but these people exist.<br>
<br>
Yes, poverty hits all people equally, but racism in hiring exists and it's pretty damn pervasive, adding a little extra difficulty for many minority job applicants.<br>
<br>
-Kitreana <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ozzamar>Ozzamar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/26/03 12:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=521.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Michigan Affirmative Action.</span><hr size=1> I can't see why there's such a big stink over the Supreme Court decision. They didn't exactly give a ringing endorsement to affirmative action in college admissions practices. Instead, the court recommends the individual-focused approach that requires admissions officers to take a good, long look at the applicants.<br>
